naming conventions



1. When using CamelCase names, capitalize all letters of an abbreviation (e.g. HTTPServer)

2. Package names should be all lower case

                When multiple words are needed, an underscore should separate them

                It is usually preferable to stick to 1 word names

3. Module names should be all lower case

                When multiple words are needed, an underscore should separate them

                It is usually preferable to stick to 1 word names

4. Class names should follow the UpperCaseCamelCase convention

                Python’s built-in classes, however are typically lowercase words

                Exception classes should end in “Error”

5. Global variables should be all lowercase

                Words in a global variable name should be separated by an underscore

6. Instance variable names should be all lower case

                Words in an instance variable name should be separated by an underscore

                Non-public instance variables should begin with a single underscore

                If an instance name needs to be mangled, two underscores may begin its name

7. Method names should be all lower case

                Words in an method name should be separated by an underscore

                Non-public method should begin with a single underscore

                If a method name needs to be mangled, two underscores may begin its name

8. Function names should be all lower case

                Words in a function name should be separated by an underscore

9. Constant names must be fully capitalized

                Words in a constant name should be separated by an underscore